coordinator review
score 4/5

  Summary Review Text

    All Reviewers believe this paper falls best into the applications category.
    The paper is generally well written and is technically sound. All seemed to
    appreciate the acquisition of requirements as a basis for the tool design.
    The paper could benefit from a few statements regarding the current state of the
    art, some indication of the end-users response to such a tool (did the effort of
    requirements gathering pay off?), and a description of how the tool might be
    effective in the domain(concrete example). It would also be valuable if reviewer
    2's  comment on capturing intent was addressed or acknowledged as a problem for
    further investigation in the paper.

  Summary Rating

    Probably accept: I would argue for accepting this paper.

  Paper Type

    Application / Design Study

  Rating

    Probably accept: I would argue for accepting this paper.

  Expertise

    Knowledgeable

  The Review

    This paper contributes a survey on a radiology visualization workflow and the
    initial results of a prototype of a visual storytelling tool that allows users to
    perform data exploration and present findings based on provenance.

    Strengths and weaknesses? The strength of the paper lies in its interesting
    application and its being well written.  The primary weakness is the lack of
    explanation of the current state of radiology analysis software and what drove
    this software to be produced. Do current software systems lack the storytelling?
    The work is relevant to the EuroVis Conference.
    The work is adequately referenced, though I would have liked to have seen some
    information on the existing software used by the radiologists and how this
    software is different.
    The paper is technically sound.
    The work could be reproduced by a technically competent graduate student.
    The exposition is clear, though I had a difficult time understanding figures 3 and
    4 and spent some time going back to the text, I am not sure how to improve on that
    in the 4 page limit (I think enough information is provided).
    Perhaps figure 3 could be halved to make room for the comparison against existing
    methodologies?

    Figure 1.  All of the text needs to be a bit larger and thus legible.
    I like figure 2.
    In Figure 3 my problem started because the caption notes there are four levels of
    abstraction, but only three are labeled in the image. It took me a while to figure
    out  the first one was the whole thing… The right side is perhaps redundant and
    space consumptive.

